In addition to the emergency action and notification procedures described earlier in this document, RSI complies with and maintains numerous other operational programs for the purpose of promoting employee safety and minimizing potential hazards and environmental impacts to the surrounding community. These include, but are not limited to, the following:



a. Emergency Hotline notifications; 

b. Spill, Prevention, Control and Countermeasure (SPCC) Plan and spill response equipment; 

c. RCRA Contingency Plan; 

d. Hot Work Permit Program; 

e. Safety Lockout-Tagout (LOTO) Program; 

f. Extensive safety programs throughout RSI's field locations; 

g. Fire Prevention Plan; 

h. Bomb Threat Plan; 

i. Process Safety Management (PSM) program;

o. Training in support of the certification of operators;

j. Job Safety Analyses (JSAs);

k. Confined Space Entry (CSE) procedures; 

l. Injury Investigation Procedure and Root Cause Analysis; 

m. New and Altered Equipment Inspection (Management of Change); 

n. Outside Contractor Review Policy; 

o. Community Emergency Response Coordination Policy; 

p. Various emergency communication systems throughout the facility such as audible alarms, paging systems, hand-held radios, phones, and visual alarms; 

q. Right-To-Know Notification Programs administered by federal, State, and local agencies (Tier 2 Chemical Inventory Reports, SARA Title III, etc.); and

r. Extensive and detailed employee training in all phases of job-related safety, chemical awareness, spill response, HAZCOM, emergency procedures, emergency/spill/release notification, and other programs.
